Love it. Here‚Äôs a copy-paste, battle-tested zero-shot prompt that makes a top agent produce a step-by-step, code-anchored explainer of every circuit breaker in your repo‚Äîcovering design, failure detection, fallbacks, observability, edge cases, and PE-grade recommendations.

‚∏ª

Zero-Shot Prompt ‚Äî ‚ÄúExplain Every Circuit Breaker in Our Codebase (Step-by-Step, PE-Ready)‚Äù

Role
Act as a Staff/Principal engineer at a billion-dollar startup: concise, accurate, SRE-aligned, and documentation-first.

Context
	‚Ä¢	We use an in-house circuit breaker pattern (e.g., CircuitBreaker(fail_max=5, reset_timeout=60, success_threshold=2)), possibly via ent_pycore or local equivalents.
	‚Ä¢	Codebase layout: src/ (code), tests/ (pytest).
	‚Ä¢	Primary files likely include src/circuit_breaker.py and call sites across services/clients.
	‚Ä¢	Objective: explain, not redesign‚Äîproduce a precise, code-referenced walkthrough of how each breaker works, how failure is detected, and what the fallback is.

Inputs You Can Assume
	‚Ä¢	Repo root: <<REPO_ROOT>> (default: current working tree)
	‚Ä¢	Key modules: <<PRIMARY_FILES_OR_GLOBS>> (e.g., src/**/circuit_breaker*.py, src/**/*client*.py, src/**/*service*.py)
	‚Ä¢	Runtime config sources in order of precedence (override if code differs): ENV ‚Üí config file ‚Üí code defaults.
	‚Ä¢	If ent_pycore is a distribution/namespace, use AST + safe import guards to find its exported CB pieces.

Task
Produce a single Markdown report that explains every circuit breaker instance and its behavior, with code pointers and runnable reproductions.

Method (required)
	1.	Discover all CBs
	‚Ä¢	Statically (AST) find CircuitBreaker(...) and wrappers; include custom factories or decorators.
	‚Ä¢	For each instance, resolve thresholds/timeouts/success criteria and where they come from (ENV, config, defaults).
	2.	Trace usage
	‚Ä¢	Build a concise call graph from entrypoint ‚Üí CB ‚Üí upstream dependency (e.g., LLM API).
	‚Ä¢	Note sync vs async, thread/process safety, and whether the breaker is per-dependency or global.
	3.	Explain behavior step-by-step
	‚Ä¢	Show state machine (Closed ‚Üí Open ‚Üí Half-Open), with what triggers transitions (consecutive failures vs error-rate window), and timers (cool-down/reset).
	‚Ä¢	Clarify what counts as ‚Äúfailure‚Äù: exception types, status codes, timeouts, circuit open rejections.
	‚Ä¢	Describe fallbacks (cached value, degraded response, null-object, fast-fail with user-friendly message).
	4.	Observability mapping
	‚Ä¢	List emitted metrics/logs/traces, names & labels; sample queries (Prometheus) and suggested alerts (flapping, open too long, probe failures).
	5.	Edge cases & hazards
	‚Ä¢	Double-wrapping, async + blocking mix, global state, multi-process workers, config hot-reload, high-cardinality metrics, retry storms.
	6.	Mini reproduction harness
	‚Ä¢	Provide simple, runnable code snippets or pytest examples that trigger: normal success, consecutive failures to Open, Half-Open probe success/fail, timeout path.
	7.	Prioritized recommendations
	‚Ä¢	P0/P1 suggestions to harden behavior, improve observability, or fix pitfalls‚Äîwithout changing public APIs unless strongly justified.

Output Format (strict, in order)
	1.	# Executive Summary
	‚Ä¢	One paragraph: how many CBs found, where, and headline risks or confidence level.
	2.	# Inventory of Circuit Breakers (table)

ID	Module:Line	Breaker Var	Upstream/Callsite	Policy (fail_max / reset_timeout / success_threshold)	Failure Signals Counted	Fallback



	3.	# State Machine & Semantics
	‚Ä¢	Mermaid stateDiagram-v2 with transitions & timers.
	‚Ä¢	Bulleted rules for what opens/closes; how Half-Open probes work; what‚Äôs ignored (e.g., 4xx vs 5xx).
	4.	# Per-Breaker Deep Dive (repeat per CB instance)
	‚Ä¢	Path & code refs: src/.../file.py:L123 (show small, focused snippet).
	‚Ä¢	Config resolution: ENV keys, config keys, defaults; resolved effective values.
	‚Ä¢	Call flow (Mermaid sequence diagram) from endpoint/function ‚Üí CB ‚Üí upstream.
	‚Ä¢	Failure taxonomy: exceptions/status codes/timeouts that trip the CB.
	‚Ä¢	Fallback behavior: exact return shape/examples; user impact.
	‚Ä¢	Concurrency model: thread/process safety notes; async peculiarities.
	‚Ä¢	Instrumentation: metric/log names & sample entries.
	5.	# Reproduction Recipes
	‚Ä¢	Pytest examples (or curl/script) to demonstrate:
	‚Ä¢	normal path,
	‚Ä¢	N consecutive failures ‚Üí Open,
	‚Ä¢	cool-down ‚Üí Half-Open,
	‚Ä¢	success_threshold successes ‚Üí Closed,
	‚Ä¢	timeout vs error differentiation.
	‚Ä¢	Show expected outputs and /cb/state (if available).
	6.	# Observability & Alerting
	‚Ä¢	Metrics list, low-cardinality labels, example PromQL (or pseudo):
	‚Ä¢	open duration SLI, state transition counter, probe success rate.
	‚Ä¢	Alert sketches: breaker flapping, breaker stuck Open, sudden rise in open rejections.
	7.	# Edge Cases & Known Gaps
	‚Ä¢	E.g., double wrap, per-tenant breakers, retries causing thundering herd, multi-worker desync.
	8.	# Recommendations (P0/P1/P2)
	‚Ä¢	Actionable, scoped changes; risk & effort notes; suggested owners.
	9.	# Appendix
	‚Ä¢	AST/grep queries used, config key map, longer code excerpts if needed.

Acceptance Criteria
	‚Ä¢	Every circuit breaker in the codebase is listed with module:line references and resolved config values.
	‚Ä¢	Clear, step-by-step narrative of how failure is detected and exactly what fallback returns.
	‚Ä¢	Includes state diagram + sequence diagrams, runnable reproduction snippets, and concrete alert ideas.
	‚Ä¢	Uses precise language (no vague ‚Äúmay/should‚Äù unless truly unknown; then call it out as an assumption).
	‚Ä¢	No third-party CB design theory unless tied back to our code.

House Rules
	‚Ä¢	Be concise but specific. Quote only the minimal code needed to explain.
	‚Ä¢	Do not expose secrets; keep example logs/metrics PII-safe.
	‚Ä¢	If something is unknown or inferred, label it ‚ÄúAssumption‚Äù and proceed.

Optional Inputs (fill if known)
	‚Ä¢	<<ENV_KEYS>> for CB config (e.g., CB_FAIL_MAX, CB_RESET_TIMEOUT, CB_SUCCESS_THRESHOLD).
	‚Ä¢	<<UPSTREAMS>> names and SLIs/SLOs to anchor recommendations.
	‚Ä¢	Whether the repo exposes /cb/state//metrics; if not, note how to emulate.

‚∏ª

Pro tips to strengthen your prompt even more
	‚Ä¢	Pin scope: add explicit file globs or entrypoints the agent must analyze.
	‚Ä¢	Give SLOs: target success rate/latency/error budget window to contextualize fallbacks.
	‚Ä¢	Name env keys: so config resolution is deterministic.
	‚Ä¢	Ask for risk-ranked recos with estimated effort (S/M/L) to help prioritization.
	‚Ä¢	Require runnable recipes: reviewers can verify behavior in minutes.

If you want, paste your repo paths and ENV keys and I‚Äôll pre-fill the placeholders for you.


